org.logicmill.util

Interface LongHashable


  • public interface LongHashable
    An object that can return a 64-bit hash code. This interface is intended to be used in conjunction with implementations of LargeHashMap<K,V> and associated implementations of LargeHashMap.KeyAdapter<K>. Specifically, implementations of LargeHashMap may provide a default key adapter along these lines:
    
        public class DefaultKeyAdapter<K> 
        implements LargeHashMap.KeyAdapter<K> {
                @Override
                public long getLongHashCode(Object key) {
                        return ((LongHashable)key).getLongHashCode();
                }
                @Override
                public boolean keyMatches(K mapKey, Object key) {
                        return mapKey.equals(key);
                }
        }
    When the responsibility for providing a 64-bit hash code is shifted from the key adapter to the key class itself, then the responsibility for determining equivalence likewise shifts from KeyAdapter.keyMatches to the equals(Object) method on the key class. Thus, the contract for getLongHashCode() is essentially the same as Object.hashCode():
    • Whenever it is invoked on the same object more than once during an execution of a Java application, the getLongHashCode() method must consistently return the same long value, provided no information used in equals(Object) comparisons on the object is modified. This long value need not remain consistent from one execution of an application to another.
    • If two objects are equal according to the equals(Object) method, then calling the getLongHashCode() method on each of the two objects must produce the same long value result.
    • It is not required that if two objects are unequal according to the equals(Object) method, then calling the getLongHashCode() method on each of the two objects must produce distinct results.
    Author:
    David Curtis
    See Also:
    LargeHashMap.KeyAdapter, LargeHashMap
